Since Uwamariya started growing coffee in 1997, she says her production has quadrupled. Her family’s quality of life now reflects the windfall that many smallholder farmers have enjoyed thanks to shifts in growing practices and increased demand from specialty buyers like Peet’s Coffee.“Because of coffee, we get school fees for our kids, we raise animals — cows, goats and chickens,” says Uwamariya. “We bought this land and built a new house.”Like many farmers here, Uwamariya carefully maintains her coffee trees to produce the distinctive beans that have fueled the demand for specialty coffee in the United States, a movement sparked a half-century ago by Alfred Peet, the founder of Peet's Coffee.The son of a Dutch roaster, Peet was born into the trade in the Netherlands. He traveled the world learning about coffee and tea before settling in Northern California in the 1950s and making his mark in the 1960s food revolution. In 1966, he opened his first cafe on Vine Street in Berkeley.Peet and his cafes popularized the concept of hand roasting and brewing high-quality beans for modern American palates, becoming the archetype for myriad coffee businesses in the decades that followed. Today, his eponymous brand is giving back to the farmers behind its coffee.
