Specialty coffee was a relative unknown in Rwanda just over a decade ago. But in the nearly 25 years since the country’s genocide, nonprofit and government-supported programs have helped elevate coffee from a low-priced commodity to a high-caliber crop, aiding the economy’s regrowth. For the more than 400,000 farmers who cultivate coffee here — where the average farm size is less than a quarter of an acre —  training and stewardship from roasters like Peet’s have had a direct improvement on their crop yield and quality.In fact, it was the interest and guidance from buyers like Peet’s that contributed to the development of centralized washing stations within local coffee cooperatives.“I used to process [my coffee] at home before we got a washing station in this area,” says Leonard Munyakaragwe, who has seen a sevenfold growth since he began farming the crop a decade ago. He now produces upwards of six tons of coffee in Rwanda’s Muhura District and is earning enough to have joined a savings cooperative.Despite these improvements, obtaining clean water is still challenging for many farmers, and the process can take hours.After the farming community identified water access as an urgent need, Peet’s chose to dedicate a portion of the proceeds from its annual Anniversary Blend to build water tanks with four access points. Pumping from the source to the highest point in the village, the tanks provide water for 2,000 coffee-growing families in the Gatsibo District of Rwanda’s Eastern Province.It’s a virtuous cycle, Welsh says. “We become inspired by a coffee flavor and work to create this brilliant cup,” he says. “Then we work with the farmers to figure out the best thing we can do with the proceeds.”
