Ethiopia, where coffee is said to have been discovered and where it still grows wild, is, according to Welsh, “unchallenged as the origin of the finer-tasting class of coffees.” But along with Ethiopia’s rich coffee history came a raft of aging trees and antiquated farming practices that inhibited production and quality. In the country’s Jimma region, Peet’s collaborates with nonprofit economic development groups like TechnoServe, an organization that specializes in assisting coffee growers in developing countries.Paul Stewart, TechnoServe’s global coffee director, remembers a time when farmers would dry beans outdoors. “You could see some mold on them,” Stewart recalls. Today, practices like these are a thing of the past, and smallholder farms have access to cooperative mills where they can deliver coffee to processing facilities that ensure top quality. Combined with the rising demand and prices for specialty coffee, Broscio says the training and access to quality-focused cooperatives has had “a multiplier effect” on the participants’ crop yields and incomes, allowing for investments in their farms, homes and even new businesses.“There were times when I was frustrated and even thinking of abandoning coffee farming, due to the price and the middlemen in the market,” says Nasir Eba, a coffee farmer in Jimma. “Now I am expanding my coffee farm. Thanks to my cooperative, my life and that of my family has changed.”Photography by T Brand StudioThe news and editorial staffs of The New York Times had no role in this post's preparation.
